{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:23:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:23:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2388"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2388"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.01,0.49,0.01,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47382"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2388"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2400"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43136"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47382"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a one-day history of darkening of his urine. He had an upper respiratory tract infection five days ago for which he did not take any medication and is currently recovering. He has a history of recently-diagnosed Type 2 diabetes mellitus which is diet-controlled. He takes no regular medications. On physical examination, all vital signs are within normal limits and no skin rash is detected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis urine test results are shown:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtein = +1\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose = Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKetones = Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeucocyte esterase = Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENitrites = Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECrystals = None\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERBC = 50/HPF\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite blood cells = 7/HPF\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECasts = RBC casts present\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum complement levels are normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute interstitial nephritis","Diabetic nephropathy","IgA nephropathy","Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis","Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with dark urine five days after an upper respiratory tract infection (URTI) and signs of nephritic syndrome (eg, mild proteinuria, haematuria) are consistent with the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003EIgA nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E (IgAN). IgAN presents with recurrent episodes of gross or microscopic haematuria typically within days after a URTI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother common differential that is associated with glomerulonephritis after a URTI is \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-streptococcal glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E (PSGN). However, patients usually present with PSGN two to three weeks after an URTI. In addition, PSGN is more common in children, whereas IgAN is more common in adults aged 20-30 years. C3 is usually reduced in PSGN and typically normal in IgAN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute interstitial nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute inflammation of renal interstitium and tubules after exposure to certain medications (eg, cephalosporins, fluoroquinolones, penicillins, sulphonamides). Patients can also have a fever, joint pains, skin rash, and eosinophilia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects patients with a long-standing history of diabetes (and/or poorly controlled diabetes) and commonly presents with proteinuria, but not haematuria as in this patient, making this option less likely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocal segmental glomerulosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a nephrotic syndrome picture, not haematuria seen in this patient. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Haematuria and recent respiratory infection should always raise the possibility of an IgA nephropathy."],"references":["Rodrigues J, Haas M, Reich H. IgA Nephropathy. Clinical Journal of the American Society of Nephrology. 2017;12(4):677-686. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28159829/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32115"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2388"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32115"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-22T21:56:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-22T21:56:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2388"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47382"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","